2.18 Bit-wise Logical Functions вҠӨвҲ§, вҠӨвҲЁ, вҠӨвҚІ, вҠӨвҚұ, вҠӨвү , and вҠӨ=
==========================================================

The APL functions And (вҲ§), Or (вҲЁ), Nand (вҚІ), and Nor (вҚұ) operate
primarily on Boolean integers.  Primarily means that the LCM variant for
вҲ§ and the GCD variant for вҲЁ are not considered in this context.  (The
LCM and GCD variants are defined in the ISO standard and supported in
GNU APL but not in IBM APL2).

   However, probably more often than not one needs to compute Boolean
functions between the bits of arbitrary (non-Boolean) integers and not
between entire Boolean integers 0 or 1.  Although that is possible to do
in standard APL, the procedure is fairly awkward and, more importantly,
inefficient:

   вҖў convert every integer argument X to a 64-item Boolean vector
     XвҶҗ(64вҚҙ2)вҠӨX,
   вҖў call the Boolean function вҲ§, вҲЁ, вҚІ, вҚұ, =, or вү  with the converted
     arguments, and
   вҖў convert the Boolean result vector R back to the integer result
     ZвҶҗ2вҠҘR

   Note: for Boolean arguments the APL functions вү  and = can be used to
compute the more customary Boolean functions XOR and XNOR respectively.
In this context = and вү  are treated as Boolean functions even though
they accept non-Boolean arguments,

   For example, using 5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨX to display X in hex:

      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   AвҶҗ$ABBADEAD
ABBADEAD
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   BвҶҗ$00FF00FF
00FF00FF

      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҲ§ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB
00BA00AD


   With the bit-wise And (вҠӨвҲ§) the same can be achieved in a simpler
fashion and far more efficiently:

      вҚқ Traditional AND
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   AвҶҗ$ABBADEAD
ABBADEAD
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   BвҶҗ$00FF00FF
00FF00FF

      вҚқ bit-wise AND
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   A вҠӨвҲ§ B
00BA00AD

2.18.1 Dyadic вҠӨвҲ§, вҠӨвҲЁ, вҠӨвҚІ, вҠӨвҚұ, вҠӨ=, and вҠӨвү 
----------------------------------------

The dyadic forms of вҠӨвҲ§, вҠӨвҲЁ, вҠӨвҚІ, and вҠӨвҚұ are simply the bit-wise variants
of their Boolean counterparts:

      A вҠӨвҲ§ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҲ§ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. AND
      A вҠӨвҲЁ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҲЁ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. OR
      A вҠӨвҚІ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҚІ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. NAND
      A вҠӨвҚұ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҚұ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. NOR
      A вҠӨвү  B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вү  (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. XOR
      A вҠӨ= B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) = (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. NXOR or XNOR

2.18.2 Monadic вҠӨвҲЁ and вҠӨвҚұ
------------------------

вҠӨ=, вҠӨвү , and вҠӨвҚІ do not have a monadic form, but вҠӨвҲ§, вҠӨвҲЁ, and вҠӨвҚұ do.
Formally monadic вҠӨвҲЁ and вҠӨвҚұ are dyadic вҠӨвҲЁ and вҠӨвҚұ with a left argument of
0:

      вҠӨвҲЁ B    вҶҗвҶ’    0 вҠӨвҲЁ B      вҚқ real B to nearby integer
      вҠӨвҚұ B    вҶҗвҶ’    0 вҠӨвҚұ B      вҚқ bit-wise Not

   Even though Or-ing a Boolean vector with 0 itself has no effect, the
monadic вҠӨвҲЁ and вҠӨвҚұ are still useful due to their side effects: conversion
from near-integer float values to integers (monadic вҠӨвҲЁ and inversion of
the bits (monadic вҠӨвҚұ, The latter is needed since вҲј has a monadic form
and, as a consequence, вҠӨвҲј was not an option for a bit-wise Not function.

   Monadic вҠӨвҚұ B is the bit-wise Not function of its argument:

   вҠӨвҚұ B вҶҗвҶ’ 2вҠҘ ~(64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB

   Monadic вҠӨвҲЁ B converts near-integer values B into true integers:

      26 вҺ•CR    1            вҚқ integer
16
      26 вҺ•CR    1.1          вҚқ real
32
      26 вҺ•CR    1Г·1          вҚқ integer
16
      26 вҺ•CR    1.1Г·1.1      вҚқ real
32
      26 вҺ•CR    вҠӨвҲЁ 1.1Г·1.1   вҚқ integer
16

   That also works for complex numbers with a near-zero imaginary part:

      26 вҺ•CR    1.1J0Г·1.1      вҚқ real
32
      26 вҺ•CR    вҠӨвҲЁ 1.1J0Г·1.1      вҚқ integer
16

   As a matter of fact, вҠӨвҲЁ works for all near-Gaussian complex numbers,
but the effect is not visible with 26 вҺ•CR since Gaussian and
non-Gaussian complex numbers have the same cell type in GNU APL.

2.18.3 Monadic вҠӨвҲ§
-----------------

The ISO standard defines two different concepts to decide if a real
number R is close to an integer I,
   вҖў the real number R is said to be near to integer I if the absolute
     value of I-R is smaller than some small constant called the integer
     tolerance in ISO and system tolerance in IBM APL2.  The integer
     tolerance is typically platform dependent (1EВҜ10 in GNU APL).

   вҖў the real number R is said to be equal to integer I within вҺ•CT if
     the absolute value of (I-R)/I is smaller than вҺ•CT.

   The first concept is an absolute distance from a real R to a nearby
integer I while the second concept is a relative distance (larger
numbers are allowed to be farther away from a nearby integer than
smaller numbers).  The two concepts differ in the same way that absolute
and relative errors do.

   Now, all bit-wise functions described so far use the first concept,
i,e, if their arguments are real or complex, then the smallest distance
to a (nearby) integer must not exceed the integer tolerance.  In some
contexts that could be difficult to achieve and for that reason GNU APL
provides monadic вҠӨвҲ§ which works like вҠӨвҲЁ except that the permitted
distance from a nearby integer is now controlled by вҺ•CT rather than by
the integer tolerance.

   All bit-wise logical functions throw a DOMAIN ERROR if an argument is
not close enough to an integer.  The integer tolerance is typically
smaller than вҺ•CT and in that case вҠӨвҲ§ is a little more tolerant than вҠӨвҲЁ
regarding the distance to nearby integers.  In addition вҠӨвҲ§ gives the
user (via вҺ•CT) more control over the permitted tolerance for real
numbers in the neighborhood of integers.

2.18.4 Character Arguments for Monadic вҠӨвҚұ and Dyadic вҠӨвҲ§, вҠӨвҲЁ, ==, and вү вү 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

Some of the bit-wise operations are allowed to have characters as their
right argument.  If the right argument is a character then the result is
a character as well.  This can be useful for masking purposes such as
extracting the lower 7 bits of 8-bit bytes containing ASCII characters.

   The characters involved are treated as 32 bit quantities:

      5вҺ•CR 'A'
41
      5вҺ•CR вҠӨвҚұ'A'            вҚқ Note that 5вҺ•CR aka. вҺ•CR.to_HEX ANDs with $FF
BE

      256 256 256 256вҠӨ вҺ•UCS вҠӨвҚұ 'A'      вҚқ вҠӨвҚұ 'A' is FFFFFFBE
255 255 255 190
      256 256 256 256вҠӨ$FFFFFFBE
255 255 255 190


