2.19 Generalized вҚі
==================

2.19.1 Generalized monadic вҚі
----------------------------

The standard function Interval (ZвҶҗвҚіB) requires its argument B to be a
positive integer scalar or a length 1 integer vector.  The result ZвҶҗвҚіB
then contains all possible consecutive integer values having shape B.

   Generalized monadic вҚі extends this concept to integer vectors B with
more than 1 element.  The result ZвҶҗвҚіB again contains all possible
indices of a value which has shape B, but the rank of B can now be more
than 1.  The items of Z are nested integer vectors consecutive along
each axis of B as opposed to integer scalars in the standard case.

2.19.2 Generalized dyadic вҚі
---------------------------

The standard function Index Of (ZвҶҗAвҚіB) requires its left argument A to
be a scalar or a vector of rank 1.  The items of the result Z are the
(first) positions (= indices) of the matching items of B in A (for the
items found in A) or else вҺ•IO+вҚҙA (which is an invalid index of A) for
the items of B that are not found in A.

   Generalized dyadic вҚі extends this concept to find the (first) indices
of the corresponding items of B in A (in ravel order) where the rank of
A is > 1.  Each item of the result Z is then either a nested integer
vector (if the item was found) or - different from the standard case (!)
- the empty vector вҚ¬ if the item was not found).


