2.20 вҢ№[X] - QR Factorization
============================

ZвҶҗвҢ№[X] B computes a QR factorization of the real or complex matrix B.
The axis argument X is used to clear near-0 matrix items to exactly 0.0
during the computation.  Set XвҶҗвҺ•CT if unsure.

   The result Z is a triple (QT R Ri)вҶҗZ with the following properties.
Let вҚҙB=(M, N).

   * QT is an orthogonal MГ—M matrix, i.e QT^{-1} = QT^{T}, and QT +.Г—
вҚүQT is the MГ—M identity matrix I_{M} (with I_{M}вҶҗвҲҳ.=вҚЁвҚіM).

   * R is an upper triangular MГ—N matrix, i.e.  R[m;n] = 0 for n < m,
and

   * Ri is the inverse of R, i.e.  Ri +.Г— R is the identity matrix
I_{N}.

   * (вҚүQT) +.Г— R = B.

   Note that, unlike in standard QR factorizations, the matrix QT
returned by вҢ№[X] is already inverted (i.e.  transposed since QT is
orthogonal).  The reason is that the algorithm used can transpose Q with
no extra cost and usually the first step after a QR factorization is to
transpose the returned Q matrix.  This first transpose step is therefore
not needed.

