2.20.1 The Impact of вҺ•CT for вҢ№
------------------------------

Due to the lack of a better place we describe here how вҺ•CT is used in
the various вҢ№ functions.

2.20.1.1 AвҢ№B and вҢ№B
...................

The first step in the computation of AвҢ№B or вҢ№B is the estimation of the
number of linearly independent columns of B. If that number is smaller
than the total number of columns (IOW some columns of B are linearly
dependent) then a DOMAIN ERROR is raised before the computation of вҢ№B
starts.  Although B may be over-determined (so it may have more rows
than columns and in that case the rows of B cannot be linearly
independent) it may not have linearly dependent columns.

   Now, for every real or complex number вҚә does вҺ•CT define a range of
nearby numbers that are considered equal to вҚә even though they are,
computationally speaking, different?

   In the same fashion, let B be a matrix with linearly dependent
columns.  For every such B does вҺ•CT define a range of nearby matrices
that are also considered linearly dependent even though they are,
strictly speaking, linearly independent?  As a matter of fact, the
probability that the columns of B are strictly linearly independent
decreases as the size of the matrix grows.  If a matrix has linearly
dependent columns, then every new row added to the matrix can make it
linearly independent, but not the other way around.

   The consequence for the user of GNU APL is the following.  If GNU APL
raises a DOMAIN ERROR caused by the supposedly linearly dependent
columns of some matrix B then there are two possibilities:

  1. the columns of B are indeed linearly dependent, e.g.  вҢ№BвҶҗ2 2вҚҙ3 4.
     In this case there is no way to compute вҢ№B.
  2. the columns of B are only close (as controlled by вҺ•CT) to some
     other strictly linearly dependent matrix.  In this case (which is
     far more likely than the other), one may decrease вҺ•CT until the
     matrix becomes linearly independent.  For example, вҢ№B may raise a
     DOMAIN ERROR with the default вҺ•CTвҶҗ1EВҜ13 but not with вҺ•CTвҶҗ1EВҜ15.
     However, one should use this technique with great care because
     matrices that are nearly linearly dependent tend to produce
     significant rounding errors in the result.

2.20.1.2 вҢ№[X] B
...............

The integer scalar X chooses one of currently two different algorithms
that compute a QR factorization of a matrix B:

   вҖў вҢ№[1]B uses the algorithm published by Garry Helzer in APL Quote
     Quad in 1990.
   вҖў вҢ№[2]B uses a LApack algorithm (xGELSY). This algorithm uses вҺ•CT in
     the same way as described above for вҢ№B and AвҢ№B.
   вҖў for backward compatibility with older versions of GNU APL, a real
     scalar X in вҢ№[X]B uses вҢ№[1]B if X < 0.1 and вҢ№[2]B otherwise.  The
     scalar X is used instead of вҺ•CT. Do not use this case in new code.

   The Helzer algorithm recursively factors a NГ—N matrix, a (N-1)Г—(N-1)
matrix, a (N-2)Г—(N-2) matrix, and so forth.  After every step of that
recursion, all matrix items close to 0.0 are set to exactly 0.0.

   GNU APL uses вҺ•CT in the same way as the Helzer alogrithm, i.e.  to
decide if a matrix item close to 0.0 shall be set to 0.0 or not (APL
functions A TOL X and A CPR B, where Helzer leaves it open how to
implement A TOL X and A CPR B). GNU APL uses the example implementation
given in the Helzer paper.  The TOL and CPR functions seem to be related
to what is elsewhere known as the condition number of the matrix that is
being factorized.  In the LApack case, the parameter RCOND of FORTRAN
function xcDGELSY is set to вҺ•CT.


