2.29 вҺ•JSON - JSON Parsing
=========================

GNU APL provides вҺ•JSON for decoding and encoding JSON strings and files.
A (valid) JSON string is mapped to an APL value as follows:

   вҖў JSON value вҶҗвҶ’ structured or non-structured APL value
   вҖў JSON number вҶҗвҶ’ APL number
   вҖў JSON string вҶҗвҶ’ APL string
   вҖў JSON literal вҶҗвҶ’ enclosed APL string (one of either вҠӮвҖҷnullвҖҷ,
     вҠӮвҖҷtrueвҖҷ, or вҠӮвҖҷfalseвҖҷ )
   вҖў JSON array вҶҗвҶ’ APL vector
   вҖў JSON object вҶҗвҶ’ structured APL value (associative array)

2.29.1 Monadic вҺ•JSON
--------------------

ZвҶҗвҺ•JSON B converts the string B into an APL value according to the
mapping above.  If that fails then command )MORE provides information
about the error and where in B the error was detected.

2.29.2 Dyadic вҺ•JSON
-------------------

ZвҶҗA вҺ•JSON B performs one of the following conversions:

   вҖў ZвҶҗ0 вҺ•JSON B is the same as monadic ZвҶҗвҺ•JSON B.

   вҖў ZвҶҗ1 вҺ•JSON B is like ZвҶҗ0 вҺ•XML B, except that B is not the JSON
     string itself but the name of a file from which a JSON string is
     read.

   вҖў ZвҶҗ2 вҺ•JSON B is the inverse of ZвҶҗ0 вҺ•XML B. It converts an APL value
     to a JSON string.

   вҖў ZвҶҗ3 вҺ•JSON B is like 2 вҺ•JSON B, except that the member names (keys)
     of all JSON objects are sorted alphabetically.  That is of little
     use (but costs performance) if Z is not displayed but processed
     further, but it could help troubleshooting when Z is displayed and
     the number of keys in Z is large.


