2.32 вҺ•PLOT - Plot Data
======================

вҺ•PLOT is a function for visualizing numerical APL values.  The values to
be plotted are provided as the right argument of вҺ•PLOT while the
optional left argument controls details of the output, such as the plot
window size, colors for plot lines, points, and grids, etc.

   The general syntax of вҺ•PLOT is:

   вҺ•PLOT вҚ¬       вҚқ show a list of attributes and their default values
   HвҶҗвҺ•PLOT B     вҚқ plot B with all attributes set to their default values
   HвҶҗA вҺ•PLOT B   вҚқ plot B with specified default attributes overridden
   вҺ•PLOT H       вҚқ close the plot window with handle H
   вҺ•PLOT  0      вҚқ verbosity: OFF (no debug output)
   вҺ•PLOT ВҜ1      вҚқ verbosity: ON (print attribute values before plotting)
   вҺ•PLOT ВҜ2      вҚқ verbosity: DEBUG (also print debug information)
   вҺ•PLOT ВҜ3      вҚқ close all plot windows
   вҺ•PLOT ВҜ6      вҚқ return all open plot window handles H

* Menu:

* Output File Format::

2.32.1 The Plot Data B
----------------------

The plot data B can be a vector (for a single plot line to be drawn) or
a matrix (in that case one plot line per matrix row is drawn, by default
in different colors).  Each data item has to be numeric and represents
one point in the plot.  The points that are adjacent in a row of the
matrix are connected by lines.  By default plotted points are black and
the lines connecting them are green (for the first plot line).  However,
all colors used, all diameters of points, and all thicknesses of the
lines can be fine-tuned by overriding the default values (see dyadic A
вҺ•PLOT B below).

2.32.1.1 Complex Plot Data B
............................

If a data item B[N] or B[row;N] is complex, say B[N] = x + iy.  then it
is placed (after some scaling) at position (x, y) of the plot.  The
X-range [Xmin ...  Xmax] of the plot is then determined by the real
parts of B, and the Y-range [Ymin ...  Ymax] of the plot is determined
by the imaginary parts of B. That is:

Xmin вҶҗ вҢҠ/,9в—ӢB    вҚқ smallest real part of B
Xmax вҶҗ вҢҲ/,9в—ӢB    вҚқ largest real part of B
Ymin вҶҗ вҢҠ/,11в—ӢB   вҚқ smallest imaginary part of B
Ymax вҶҗ вҢҲ/,11в—ӢB   вҚқ largest imaginary part of B

   Example (plot a circle (actually: a regular 20-gon)):

      вҺ•PLOT +вҢҝ1 0J1Г—[1]1 2 вҲҳ.в—Ӣ (0,вҚі2Г—N) Г— в—ӢГ·NвҶҗ10

   produces this plot window (only visible in the HTML version of this
document; in text mode see file doc/PLOT_circle.png):

␀[image src="PLOT_circle.png"␀]


2.32.1.2 Real Plot Data B
.........................

On the other hand, if a data item B[N] or B[row;N] is real, then it is
placed at position (N, x) of the plot.  The X-range is then [вҺ•IO ...
вҺ•IO + ВҜ1вҶ‘вҚҙB] and the Y-range [Y_{min} ...  Y_{max}] of the plot is
determined by the values of B. That is:

Xmin вҶҗ вҺ•IO             вҚқ smallest real part of B
Xmax вҶҗ ВҜ1 + вҺ•IO + вҚҙB   вҚқ largest real part of B
Ymin вҶҗ вҢҠ/,B            вҚқ smallest value in B
Ymax вҶҗ вҢҲ/,B            вҚқ largest value in B

   Example:

      вҺ•PLOT 0 1 ВҜ1 2 ВҜ2 3 ВҜ3

   produces this plot window (only visible in the HTML version of this
document; in text mode see file doc/PLOT_zigzag.png):

␀[image src="PLOT_zigzag.png"␀]


   NOTE: In theory one can also mix real and complex values, even though
doing so makes little sense.  If at least one item of the plot data B is
complex, then all real items in B are taken as complex with imaginary
part 0.

2.32.2 The Plot Attributes A
----------------------------

There are a number of attributes like colors, point sizes, line widths,
etc.  that control how the resulting plot will look.

   Similar to вҺ•CR and вҺ•FIO, an empty argument B in вҺ•PLOT B displays a
list of the arguments.  The list of arguments grows over time and
therefore the list displayed by вҺ•PLOT вҚ¬ may be more up-to-date than this
description.  For example:


   вҺ•PLOT Usage:

   вҺ•PLOT B     with вҚҙвҚҙB > 0: plot B with default attribute values
   вҺ•PLOT B     with integer scalar B: special вҺ•PLOT functions
   A вҺ•PLOT B   plot B with attribute overrides specified by A

   A is a nested vector of strings.
   Each string A[i] has the form "Attribute: Value"
   Colors are specified either as #RGB or as #RRGGBB or as RR GG BB)

   The attributes understood by вҺ•PLOT and their default values are:

   1. Global (plot window) Attributes:

caption:            вҺ•PLOT          (plot window caption)
output_filename:                   (output file name)
auto_close:         0              (= do not close X window automatically)
                   (1)             (= close if file was written successfully)
                   (2)             (= always close X window automatically)
with_border:        1              (= write plot area and window borders)
                   (0)             (= write only plot area to output file)
pw_pos_X:           50 pixel       (plot window position X)
pw_pos_Y:           50 pixel       (plot window position Y)
border_width:       10 pixel       (width of the window border)
