2.36 вҺ•RVAL - Random APL value
=============================

The standard way to produce random numbers is the primitive function ?
aka.  Roll.  Roll returns a simple random array whose ravel elements are
positive integers chosen in a (pseudo-) random fashion.  While this is
sufficient for many applications, one sometimes needs APL values whose
randomness not only affects the ravel elements themselves, but also
other aspects like:

   вҖў the rank of the value,
   вҖў the shape of the value,
   вҖў the data type of the ravel elements, and
   вҖў the depth (nesting) of the values.

   Such values can be produced with system function вҺ•RVAL. The main use
case for вҺ•RVAL is the production of test data for the interpreter, but
вҺ•RVAL might be useful for other purposes as well.

2.36.1 General
--------------

In general, monadic вҺ•RVAL B, returns a single random APL value Z, while
dyadic A RVAL B is used to control the properties of subsequently
generated random APL values returned by monadic вҺ•RVAL.

   The typical use of вҺ•RVAL is to first call A вҺ•RVAL B zero or more
times to override individual default properties of the subsequently
produced values, followed by one or more calls of monadic вҺ•RVAL B.

   The default properties, i.e.  the properties used unless they were
overridden by dyadic A вҺ•RVAL B, are:

Rank:  0
Shape: 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 (initially irrelevant since Rank = 0)
Type:  0 1 0 0 0       (only integer random values)
Max. Depth: 4          (initially irrelevant since type = 0 1 0 0 0)

   With these default properties, every call of monadic вҺ•RVAL B returns
an integer scalar.

2.36.2 Dyadic вҺ•RVAL
-------------------

The left argument A of A вҺ•RVAL B determines which aspect of the
subsequent random APL values shall be controlled.  A is an integer
scalar:

   вҖў A=0 controls the state of the underlying random number generator,

   вҖў A=1 controls the ranks of the subsequent random APL values,

   вҖў A=2 controls the shapes of the subsequent random APL values,

   вҖў A=3 controls the data types in the ravels of the subsequent random
     APL values, and

   вҖў A=4 controls a maximum depth of the subsequent random APL values.

2.36.2.1 Control of the underlying random number generator: 0 вҺ•RVAL B
.....................................................................

вҺ•RVAL uses the standard C function random_r().  For this reason вҺ•RVAL is
only available on platforms which use glibc, for example all GNU/Linux
systems.

   Every random number generator has a state (similar to вҺ•RL for вҖҷ?вҖҷ).
While the primitive ?  keeps its state in вҺ•RL, i.e.  in the workspace,
вҺ•RVAL has no associated system variable like вҺ•RL which keeps its state.
Instead, the user needs to store the state of вҺ•RVAL in a workspace
variable if the workspace shall be stored and continued at a later
point.  This rarely happens, therefore no effort was spent on
implementing another system variable.  For the same reason, the state of
вҺ•RVAL survives )CLEAR.

   The current state of вҺ•RVALвҖҷs random number generator can be retrieved
with:

      STATE вҶҗ 0 вҺ•RVAL ''

   The state changes with every call of monadic вҺ•RVAL. The random number
generator can later be restored to the same state like this:

      0 вҺ•RVAL STATE

   Restoring the state is needed when the same sequence of random values
shall be generated again.  The random number generators of ?  and вҺ•RVAL
are independent; generating a random number or random value with one
does not change the state of the other.

2.36.2.2 Control of the ranks: 1 вҺ•RVAL B
........................................

The rank of subsequently generated random values can be controlled with
1 вҺ•RVAL B as follows:

   вҖў If B is a non-negative scalar with 0 вүӨ B < MAX_RANK then the
     subsequently generated random values will have the fixed rank B.
     MAX_RANK is a ./configurable constant with a default of 8.

   вҖў If B is a negative scalar with 0 > B > -MAX_RANK then the ranks of
     the subsequently generated random values will be chosen at random
     between 0 and -B (inclusive).  All possible ranks 0 ...  B will
     have the same probability P = 100Г·1-B %.

   вҖў Otherwise B must be a vector of positive integers.  The integers
     are the relative frequencies of the ranks 0, 1, ...  MAX_RANK
     respectively.  Too many integers (i.e.  MAX_RANK > вҚҙB) will raise a
     LENGTH ERROR while fewer (than MAX_RANK) are set to 0.

   1 вҺ•RVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  1 вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬ will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 1 вҺ•RVAL.

   Examples:

   вҖў 1 вҺ•RVAL 2 will produce only matrices,

   вҖў 1 вҺ•RVAL ВҜ2 will produce scalars, vectors or matrices, each with a
     probability of 100Г·3 %, and

   вҖў 1 вҺ•RVAL 50 30 20 will produce scalars with probability 50%, vectors
     with probability 30%, and matrices with probability 20%.  The
     numbers need not add up to 100, but will be scaled accordingly.

2.36.2.3 Control of the shapes: 2 вҺ•RVAL B
.........................................

The shapes of subsequently generated random values can be controlled
with 2 вҺ•RVAL B as follows.

   B must be a vector of positive or negative integers.  Vectors longer
than MAX_RANK + 1 will give a LENGTH ERROR while vectors shorter than
MAX_RANK + 1 will be filled with 1 until the length of B becomes
MAX_RANK + 1.

   If an element B_{i} of the resulting shape B = B_{1} ...  B_{MAXRANK}
is вүҘ 0 then the corresponding axis i will have a fixed length of B_{i}.
If B_{i} < 0 then the length of that axis will be chosen at random with
a probability of 1Г·B_{i}.  Note that the same B can still produce
different shapes even if all B_{i} are вүҘ 0 (i.e.  if the rank is also
chosen at random).

   2 вҺ•RVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  2 вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬, will not change anything and can be
used to query the current setting for 2 вҺ•RVAL.

   Example:

1 вҺ•RVAL 2        вҚқ produce matrices
2 вҺ•RVAL 3 ВҜ10    вҚқ the first axis of every matrix will have length 3, and
                 вҚқ the last axis of every matrix will vary between 0 and 10

   This will produce scalars, vectors with a fixed length of 3 and
matrices with 3 rows and between 0 and 10 columns.

2.36.2.4 Control of the data types: 3 вҺ•RVAL B
.............................................

The types (i.e.  CHARACTER, INTEGER, REAL, COMPLEX, or NESTED) of
subsequently generated random values can be controlled with 3 вҺ•RVAL B as
follows.

   B must be a vector with up to 5 positive numbers, corresponding to
the types.  Shorter vectors are filled with 0 (the corresponding types
will not occur) and longer vectors will raise a LENGTH error.

   Once the type was chosen, the ravel item will be:

   вҖў for type CHARACTER: a random character with вҺ•UCS between 0 and
     $3000 (exclusive).  Larger Unicodes typically cause display
     problems.  If you need larger Unicodes, use вҺ•UCS with random
     integers.

   вҖў for type INTEGER: a random integer with вҺ•UCS between -$80000000 and
     $7FFFFFFF.

   вҖў for type REAL: a floating point number between 0.0 and 1.0
     (exclusive)

   вҖў for type COMPLEX: a complex point number with real and imaginaty
     part between 0.0 and 1.0 (exclusive), and

   вҖў for type NESTED: a nested APL value with the same properties (rank,
     shape, and type) as their parent.

   3 вҺ•RVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  3 вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬ will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 3 вҺ•RVAL.

   Example:

      1 вҺ•RVAL 2         вҚқ produce matrices
      2 вҺ•RVAL 3 3       вҚқ produce 3Г—3 matrices
      3 вҺ•RVAL 0 50 50   вҚқ produce a mix of integer and real values
      вҺ•RVAL ''
ВҜ975954163190248487                   0.5892132425
7677327503669503253 2152001972871424768

2.36.2.5 Control of a maximum depth: 4 вҺ•RVAL B
..............................................

If the probability of generating a nested value is > 0 then the depth of
random values can become arbitrarily large and could therefore exceed
the system limit for the depth of the random value being produced.  This
can be prevented by setting a maximum depth for every value generated.
вҺ•RVAL sets the probability of the deepest allowed depth to 0.

   4 вҺ•RVAL B expects B to be a positive integer which is deepest allowed
depth;

   An empty B, e.g.  4 вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬, will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 4 вҺ•RVAL.

2.36.2.6 monadic вҺ•RVAL B: Return a new random value
...................................................

Calling вҺ•RVAL monadically produces one new random APL value.

   The properties of that next value can be controlled by the dyadic
calls of вҺ•RVAL as described above.  If no prior dyadic call of вҺ•RVAL was
made then the properties have the following defaults:

      1 вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬    вҚқ rank (scalar)
0

      2 вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬    вҚқ shape (not used since rank = 0)
1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1

      3 вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬    вҚқ types (integer)
0 1 0 0 0

      4 вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬    вҚқ max. depth (not used since probability of NESTED = 0)
4

   That is, by default, вҺ•RVAL вҚ¬ produces random integer scalars.

   It is sometimes convenient to be able to change the properties of the
next random value without modifying (and later restoring) the properties
with dyadic вҺ•RVAL. This can be achieved with monadic вҺ•RVAL with
non-empty B.

   Let 4=вҚҙB. Then

   ZвҶҗвҺ•RVAL B does essentially:

   B[1]вҶҗ1 вҺ•RVAL B[1]
   B[2]вҶҗ2 вҺ•RVAL B[2]
   B[3]вҶҗ3 вҺ•RVAL B[3]
   B[4]вҶҗ4 вҺ•RVAL B[4]

   ZвҶҗвҺ•RVAL ''

   B[1]вҶҗ1 вҺ•RVAL B[1]
   B[2]вҶҗ2 вҺ•RVAL B[2]
   B[3]вҶҗ3 вҺ•RVAL B[3]
   B[4]вҶҗ4 вҺ•RVAL B[4]

   If 4>вҚҙB then the missing properties are not changed.

   Examples:

вҺ•RVAL 1 (,ВҜ4) (0 1)    вҚқ return a random 0-4 element integer vector
вҺ•RVAL 2 (2 2) (1 0)    вҚқ return a random 2Г—2 character array



