2.40 вҺ•XML - XML Parsing
=======================

2.40.1 Purpose
--------------

GNU APL provides вҺ•XML as a means of performing elementary manipulations
of APL character strings that are formatted according to the XML
standard.  The anticipated procedure for such modifications is something
like:

      XML_string вҶҗ "<A><B><C>Hello</C></B></A>"   вҚқ input data (usually from an .xml file)
      APL вҶҗ вҺ•XML XML_string       вҚқ convert XML_string to associative array APL
      ABC вҶҗ APL.a.b.c             вҚқ retrieve node a.b.c in APL
      APL.a.b.c вҶҗ ABC, " World"   вҚқ modify node a.b.c in APL
      Z вҶҗ вҺ•XML APL                вҚқ convert associative array APL to XML string Z

      ABC   вҚқ the original value of XML.a.b.c
Hello
      Z     вҚқ the modified XML string
<A><B><C>Hello World</C></B></A>"

   The scope (functionality) of вҺ•XML is then:

   вҖў Conversion of (valid) XML strings to associative APL arrays that
     can be more easily processed in APL than the XML strings,
   вҖў Conversion of associative APL arrays back to valid XML strings,
   вҖў Simple (at APL level) access to the data contained in XML strings,
     and
   вҖў Transparent access to those (mostly XML specific) portions of the
     XML string that are not (yet) handled by вҺ•XML; this means that the
     user of вҺ•XML shall be able to handle advanced XML aspects (like
     document type declarations (DTDs), document validation, etc.)  in
     APL without much overhead.

2.40.2 Some XML Terminology
---------------------------

An XML document is a character string with a standardized format.  The
characters must be valid XML characters as defined in the XML standard
(almost all Unicode characters except most of the ASCII control
characters).  GNU APL raises a DOMAIN ERROR when an XML document
contains invalid XML characters.

   The XML document is a sequence of adjacent sub-strings, where each
sub-string is:

   вҖў either markup (-string),
   вҖў or non-markup (-string).

   A markup (sub-)string:

   вҖў starts with character вҖҷ<вҖҷ, and
   вҖў ends with character вҖҷ>вҖҷ, and
   вҖў all other characters in the markup string differ from вҖҷ<вҖҷ and вҖҷ>вҖҷ.

   A non-markup (sub-)string:

   вҖў starts either at the beginning of the XML document or else directly
     after a markup string,
   вҖў end at the end of the document or else directly before a markup
     string, and therefore
   вҖў cannot be adjacent to another non-markup string.

   Non-markup is sometimes referred to as "unstructured text".  The
producer of an XML document has a principal choice about where to locate
the information that the document contains: in the unstructured text or
in the attribute values inside the tags.  For that reason the XML
standard is somewhat picky about keeping the unstructured text as well
as attribute values intact and requires that whitespace in non-markup
(the only allowed whitespace characters in XML being TAB, CR, LF, and
SPACE) is preserved in non-markup strings.

   As a consequence, many non-markup strings begin with LF because the
preceeding markup was on the previous line and therefore the LF after
the preceeding markup is whitespace of the non-markup and therefore
needs to be preserved.

   Every markup belongs to one of 4 categories:

   вҖў Processing instructions: "<?  ...  ?>",
   вҖў Comments: "<!вҖ” ...  вҖ”>",
   вҖў Declarations "<!  ...  !>", and
   вҖў Tags, which are either:
        вҖў Empty tags (leaf tags): "<tagname attributes...  />
        вҖў Start tags: "<tagname attributes...  >, or
        вҖў End tags: "</tagname>

   The XML tags recursively define a tree structure where:

   вҖў the nodes of the trees are either Empty Tags or else a start tag,
     followed by a (possibly empty) sequence of non-markup, comments,
     and sub-nodes (of the tree), followed by an end tag (with the same
     name as the start tag),
   вҖў the leafs of the trees are either Empty Tags or else a start tag,
     followed by a (possibly empty) sequence of non-markup and comments,
     followed by an end tag (with the same name as the start tag).  The
     difference between a leaf node and a non-leaf is therefore the
     absence of sub-nodes between a start and an end tag.
   вҖў optionally non-markup and comments before, after, and between the
     nodes.

   Processing instructions and declarations are typically located at the
beginning of the XML document and at the same level as the root of the
tree.  defined by the document.  Document type declarations are
preserved (so that they can be processed in APL), but are currently
ignored by вҺ•XML. As a consequence, entity declarations have no effect
and only the predefined XML entities (i.e.  &, <, >, вҖҷ, and ") are
recognized (and translated) by вҺ•XML.

2.40.3 How вҺ•XML maps XML documents to APL Values
------------------------------------------------

The principal mapping between XML strings and APL values is:

   вҖў XML document вҶҗвҶ’ structured (top-level) APL value or variable (= an
     associative array)
   вҖў XML node вҶҗвҶ’ structured APL (sub-) value (= an associative (sub-)
     array of either the top-level value or of another XML node)
   вҖў XML name вҶҗвҶ’ name of a member in a structured APL value
   вҖў Other вҶҗвҶ’ member value

   Every valid name in XML is also a valid name for an APL variable or
structure member.  Unfortunately, mapping XML names directly to APL
member names cannot work because:

   вҖў In any associative array the names of the members are necessarily
     distinct.  Assigning a value to an already existing member of a
     structured value overwrites the current value of that member
     instead of creating a second member with that value.  On the other
     hand, in XML nodes tags may (and frequently do) occur repeatedly.
     If an XML document contains several nodes with the same tag, then
     the applications usually knows how to interpret the order in which
     the tags occur, but this order may not be detectable at the XML
     level (i.e.  the nodes may not only have the same tag names, but
     also the same attributes and attribute values).

     The applications that use the XML document frequently require that
     the order of XML nodes with the same name remain intact when the
     document is modified.  For example, the entries of a telephone book
     may be sorted alphabetically without XML being aware of that.
     Reading, modifying, and writing back the data in the telephone book
     must therefore not destroy that order.

   вҖў Likewise, at least for readability reasons, the order of node
     attributes should not be changed.  XML documents are frequently
     processed with text tools like diff which would incorrectly show
     differences between XML documents that are equivalent from an XML
     perspective.

   вҖў Conflicts between tag names and attribute names.  In XML, the same
     name can designate an attribute in one node and a tag in another
     node.  вҺ•XML keeps all information from the < of a start tag to the
     > of an end tag in a single associative array, therefore the
     attribute names must somehow differ from the (sub-) tag names.

   вҖў Every XML node has a tag name that can be used to derive a
     corresponding APL member name.  However, the text segments between
     an XML tag and its corresponding end tag, are a mixture of
     unstructured text, XML subnodes and comments of which only the XML
     subnodes have tags of their own.  These untagged segments may,
     however, contain relevant information and, from an XML standard
     perspective, both their content and their order must be preserved.

   вҺ•XML solves these issues with a simple naming convention for all
member names in the (recursive) associative array that is produced by
monadic вҺ•XML. Every member name consists of 3 components that together
yield a valid APL variable name (and therefore a valid member name that
is understood by the APL parser):

   вҖў A single character вҚҷ, вҲҶ, or _, that indicates the role of the name
     in the XML document as follows:
        вҖў the character вҚҷ characterizes an attribute name, i.e.  a name
          that was used inside (i.e.  between < and >) of an XML start
          or leaf tag.  The character вҚҷ alone is the name of a special
          member which is present in every associative array below the
          top-level and whose value is the original XML tag name of a
          tag, or

        вҖў the character вҲҶ characterizes a name that was synthesized by
          вҺ•XML itself to tag a text (sub-) segment that has no tag of
          its own.  The corresponding XML entity was not a tag (and
          therefore had no tag name), or

        вҖў the character _ characterizes the name of an XML entity, i.e.
          a CML name that occurred between the start tag and the
          corresponding end tag (if any: leaf tags have no such
          entities)

   вҖў a position prefix of the form NN, where NN is the position of the
     member in relation to the tag to which it belongs.  The numbering
     starts at вҺ•IO and restarts at every XML start or leaf tag.

   вҖў the attribute name or tag name.  For those parts of an XML entity
     that do not have a tag name, the member name is synthesized by вҺ•XML
     and the member value will be the text in the XML document with
     predefined XML entities replaced by their single characters, i.e.:
        вҖў & for &amp,
        вҖў < for &lt,
        вҖў > for &gt,
        вҖў вҖҷ for &apos,
        вҖў " for &quot,
        вҖў вҺ•UCS nnn for &#nnn, and
        вҖў вҺ•UCS $xxx for &#xxx

   Let NN be a sequence of decimal digits.  Then only the following 4
synthesized names are produced by вҺ•XML:

   вҖў вҲҶNNcomment for XML comments, i.e.  <!вҖ” ...  вҖ”> in XML,
   вҖў вҲҶNNdeclaration for XML declarations, i.e.  <?  ...  ?> in XML,
   вҖў вҲҶNNdoctype for document type declarations, i.e.  <!DOCTYPE ...  >
     in XML
   вҖў вҲҶNNtext for unstructured (and hence untagged) text segements in
     XML.

   Every XML name (of a tag or attribute) is also a valid APL name, but
valid APL names may also contain the characters _, вҲҶ, and вҚҷ which are
not valid in XML and used in the naming convention above to clearly
separate the member names used in APL from the names used in the XML
document.

   The essence of all this is that everything that belongs to an XML
node or document, i.e.  the attributes inside a tag, the sub-nodes
between a start tag and its corresponding end tag (if any),
declarations, etc.  will be contained in a single associative array.

   Examples of APL member names (assuming вҺ•IOвҶҗ1):

      вҚҷ1              вҚқ the first member in every XML node. Its value is the node tag.
      вҲҶ1declaration   вҚқ the first member in most XML documents. E.g. <?xml version= ...>
      вҲҶ2text          вҚқ whitespace (LF) between _1вҲҶdeclaration and _3вҲҶdoctype
      вҲҶ3doctype       вҚқ DTD in XML documents that have one. E.g. <!DOCTYPE  ...
      _6Workspace     вҚқ Sub-array for <Workspace ... at position 6.
      вҚҷ1wsid          вҚқ first attribute wsid from e.g. <Workspace wsid=...
      вҚҷ2year          вҚқ second attribute year

2.40.4 Monadic вҺ•XML
-------------------

Z вҶҗ вҺ•XML B converts APL string B that contains a valid XML document to
an associative APL array Z and vice versa.

   Note: If you convert an associative APL array back to a an XML
document, the result is a possibly very long string containing several
linefeed characters.  That is OK if the string is written to a file, but
causes problems when the string is displayed and longer than вҺ•PW. The
standard APL folding of output near вҺ•PW make the string then look
somewhat garbled.  This effect can be suppressed in 2 ways:

  1. set вҺ•PW large enough, or
  2. prefix the string with вҠғ35вҺ•CR as in the examples below.

2.40.5 Dyadic вҺ•XML
------------------

Z вҶҗ A вҺ•XML B provides a number of convenience functions.  Its left
argument A is an integer function number, possibly followed by arguments
of the function number вҶ‘A.

   In the following examples, let

      XMLвҶҗ36 вҺ•CR """
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
  <Document>
    <Tag1 name='tag1'>   <!-- first tag -->
      TEXT1
      <Subtag name='subag1.1'>   <!-- first subtag -->
        SUBTEXT1_1
      </Subtag>
    </Tag1>
  </Document>
"""

APLвҶҗвҺ•XML XML

   Then

   вҖў ZвҶҗ0 вҺ•XML B is the same as monadic ZвҶҗвҺ•XML B.

   вҖў ZвҶҗ1 вҺ•XML B is like 0 вҺ•XML B, except that B is not the XML document
     (string) itself but the name of a file from which an XML document
     is read.

   вҖў ZвҶҗ2 вҺ•XML B splits an APL member path (a sequence of member names)
     into a vector P of (nested) member names.  This vector P is
     understood by the APL primitive PICK (i.e.  ZвҶҗPвҠғAPL or
     (PвҠғAPL)вҶҗvalue and can be used to address the data in an XML node.

   вҖў ZвҶҗ3 вҺ•XML B splits an APL member name (as produced by e.g.  monadic
     вҺ•XML into a 3-item vector Z. Z[1] is a single character indicating
     the category (i.e.  a character scalar вҲҶ, вҚҷ, or _).  Z[2] is the
     position (an integer scalar вүҘ вҺ•IO). Z[3] is a (nested) APL string.
     3 вҺ•XML has an inverse function ВҜ3 вҺ•XML which converts a 3-item
     vector as produced by 3 вҺ•XML back into an APL member name
     indicating the category (i.e.  _, вҲҶ, or вҚҷ) and the name from the
     XML tag:

                 8 вҺ•CR (C P N)вҶҗ3 вҺ•XML "вҲҶ2comment"
     в”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ
     в”ӮвҲҶ 2 в”ҢвҶ’в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җв”Ӯ
     в”Ӯ    в”Ӯcommentв”Ӯв”Ӯ
     в”Ӯ    в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳв”Ӯ
     в””вҲҠв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ
     
           C   вҚқ category
     вҲҶ
           P   вҚқ position
     2
           N   вҚқ (XML-) name
     comment
     
           ВҜ3 вҺ•XML C P N   вҚқ inverse of 3 вҺ•XML
     вҲҶ2comment
     

   вҖў ZвҶҗ4 вҺ•XML B is a string that shows the member names of the
     associative array B in a tree-like fashion.  For example:

           вҠғ35вҺ•CR 4 вҺ•XML APL
     XML                     
      в”Ӯ                      
      в””в”Җв”Җв”Җ Document          
            в”Ӯ                
            в””в”Җв”Җв”Җ Tag1        
                  в”Ӯ          
                  в””в”Җв”Җв”Җ Subtag

   вҖў ZвҶҗ5 вҺ•XML B is like 4 вҺ•XML but displays not only the XML tags but
     also other XML nodes (declarations, attributes, etc.):

           вҠғ35вҺ•CR 5 вҺ•XML APL
