2.41 Conditionals
=================

WARNING: GNU APL conditionals are experimental.  Use them with care and
avoid them, wherever possible, in favour of portability.  Neither the
ISO APL standard, nor IBM APL2 provide conditionals.

2.41.1 Design considerations.
-----------------------------

The author of GNU APL has, for a long time, hesitated to implement
conditionals in GNU APL. Primarily for the following reasons:

   вҖў the lack of standardization of conditionals,
   вҖў the lack of an elegant syntax that fits well into the typical
     (brief) APL programming style, and in particular
   вҖў the large number of keywords for flow control used in some other
     APL interpreters.  See below.

   The C language has six keywords for flow control: if else, for,
while, do, switch and goto.  Two of them (do and while) are redundant
and rarely used, leaving only 4 base cases.  A quick grep -c over the
100,000 top-level C++ source code lines of GNU APL reveals the following
statistics:

   вҖў 7000 if statements, 1600 of them two-sided if-then-else-endif, the
     others one-sided if-then-endif,
   вҖў 2000 for statements, 1200 of them trivial iterations over some
     array (aka.  for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) ...  ,
   вҖў 200 switch statements with an averge of 8 case clauses per switch,
   вҖў 250 while statements, and
   вҖў 70 do while statements

   In contrast, a popular non-free APL interpreter came up with a zoo of
30 or so keywords for the purpose of flow control in one way or another:

   :If :While :Repeat :For :In :InEach :Select :With :Trap :Hold
:Disposable :Else :ElseIf :AndIf :OrIf :Until :Case :CaseList :EndIf
:EndWhile :EndRepeat :EndFor :EndSelect :EndWith :EndTrap :EndHold
:EndDisposable :GoTo, :Return, :Leave :Continue

   This approach, its implementation, and its constraints raise a number
of serious problems.  To name a few:

   вҖў A rather common APL design practice is to first debug non-trivial
     APL statements in immediate execution mode and only transfer them
     into the body of defined functions when they work properly.
     However, the keywords above seem to work only in the bodies of
     defined functions but not in immediate execution mode.  The reason
     seems to be that their implementation depends on labels which are
     not available in immediate execution.

   вҖў Another rather common design practice is to limit the length of
     lines to less than 80 characters (e.g.  in the GNU coding
     conventions, https://gcc.gnu.org/codingconventions.html#Line).
     Even if it were possible to squeeze an :If :Then :Else :Endif into
     an 80 character line, and using a single whitespace around the
     keywords for readability, wastes almost 1/3 of the precious 80
     characters for keywords.  In this example, each of the COND, THEN,
     and ELSE parts must then be < 20 characters on average.  Not to
     talk about indentation to clarify the code.

   вҖў Each of the keywords has rather specific constraints as to how and
     where it can be used.  For example (to quote a simple one from a
     reference manual):

     Control words, including qualifiers such as :Else and :ElseIf, may
     occur only at the beginning of a line or expression in a
     diamond-separated statement.  The only exceptions are :In and
     :InEach which must appear on the same line within a :For
     expression.

     These constraints suggest that the keywords mentioned are merely
     syntactic sugar that covers the underlying APL structure, i.e.
     labels and computed branches.  GNU APL does not claim to be
     fundamentally different in that regard, but the syntax of the
     syntactic sugar is somewhat simpler.

   Learning from the above, the conclusions for the syntax of GNU APL
condionals were these:

  1. the syntax shall be easy to understand and consistent,
  2. the syntax shall work in immediate execution mode (as long as the
     entire conditional is provided on a single input line),
  3. to support 2., lengthy keywords shall be avoided in favour of the
     original APL style, and
  4. the syntax needs to only support those cases where the standard APL
     flow control (i.e.  вҶ’N) becomes cumbersome.  There is absolutely no
     benefit in introducing a new (and redundant) syntax when the
     standard APL mechanism is already completely adequate.

   As to the last point, almost every flow control case (in a standards
compliant APL program) falls into one of the following categories
(sorted by increasing complexity):

  1. one-sided if: if COND then THEN endif
  2. two-sided if/else: if COND then THEN else ELSE endif
  3. loop: while COND do BODY (or its less frequently used twin do BODY
     while COND)
  4. switch/case: switch ARG case CASE1 case CASE2 case ...  CASEn
     endswitch

   where THEN, ELSE, CASE1, CASE2, CASEn, and BODY are a sequence of one
or more statements, while COND or ARG control which of these sequences
(if any) shall be executed.

   Interestingly, the complexity of the above cases, when coded in APL,
increases in amost the reverse order (compared to other languages).  For
example,

  1. switch/case:
         вҶ’(ARG) / L1  L2 ...  Ln   вҚқ switch(ARG)
     L1: CASE1 в—Ҡ вҶ’L_endcase        вҚқ case 1:
     L2: CASE2 в—Ҡ вҶ’L_endcase        вҚқ case 2:
     ...
     LN: CASEn                     вҚқ case N:
     L_endcase:

  2. loop:
      Loop: BODY в—Ҡ вҶ’(COND) / Loop   вҚқ repeat BODY while COND

  3. one-sided if:
       вҶ’(!COND) / L_endif   вҚқ jump over the THEN clause
       THEN
     L_endif:

     or, not uncommon and shorter, but less portable and less readable:

       вҶ’(!COND) / вҶ‘1+вҺ•LC в—Ҡ THEN  вҚқ jump over the THEN clause to the next line

  4. two-sided if/else:
       вҶ’COND вҶ“ L_else L_then
     L_then: THEN в—Ҡ вҶ’L_endif
     L_else: ELSE
     L_endif:

   A closer look at these cases reveals that there is not much room for
syntax improvements in cases 1.  (switch) and 2.  (loop).  The
introduction of a new syntax like :Select / :Case for switches or :For /
:Endfor for loops would therefore only make matters different and
incompatible, but not better.

   In case 3.  (one-sided if) there is also not much to gain.  However,
case 3.  can be seen as a special case of case 4.  (with an empty ELSE
clause).  As a matter of consistency, a new syntax for case 4.  should
also cover case 3.

   The only cases where a new syntax could improve matters are therefore
cases 3.  and 4.

   Another consideration relates to the end marker L_endif (and would
likewise relate to L_endcase if we hadnвҖҷt already ruled that case out).
There are two reasonable syntax alternatives to handle the branch to the
end of the conditional:

  1. allow multiple statements in the THEN and ELSE clauses and mark the
     end of the ELSE clause (or, in the one-sided case 3 of the THEN
     clause with some ENDIF marker, or
  2. allow only single statement clauses (which implies the ENDIF and
     makes it obsolete.

   The design decision made in GNU APL was to go for multiple statements
because the advantage in 2.  (shorter code) looks much smaller than the
advantages of 1.  (e.g.  insertion of debug printouts into a clause).

2.41.2 Syntax
-------------

With the above considerations in mind, GNU APL decided for the following
syntax:

   вҖў one-sided if/else:
           COND вҶ’вҶ’ THEN вҶҗвҶҗ

   вҖў two-sided if/else:
           COND вҶ’вҶ’ THEN вҶҗвҶ’ ELSE вҶҗвҶҗ

   For this syntax to work, the following rules must be followed:

   вҖў The вҶ’вҶ’, вҶҗвҶ’, and вҶҗвҶҗ markers must be single tokens (2 adjacent
     Unicode characters) That is, no whitespace (and in particular no
     line feed) is permitted between the first and the second arrow.  A
     single вҶ’ is a valid APL statement (named Escape).  A linefeed
     between two вҶ’ turns the single token вҶ’вҶ’ into two valid (though most
     of the time useless) Escape statements.

   вҖў The вҶ’вҶ’, вҶҗвҶ’, and вҶҗвҶҗ tokens are end-of statement markers (as opposed
     to beginning-of statement markers).  Each marker binds to the
     non-empty statement left of it.  APL is parsed line by line, so
     there can never be a valid non-empty APL statement left of the
     first token of a line.  As a consequence, a вҶ’вҶ’ token, a вҶҗвҶ’ token,
     or a вҶҗвҶҗ token at the beginning of a line is a SYNTAX ERROR.

   вҖў The COND, THEN, and ELSE clauses shall be non-empty (!)  sequences
     of valid APL statements.  In particular:

        вҖў The condition COND shall be a single statement that evaluates
          to a 1-item Boolean array (of any rank).  The statement result
          of COND is a committed value (and therefore not displayed).

        вҖў The THEN clause shall be one or more valid statements,
          separated by в—Ҡ for more than one statement.

        вҖў The ELSE clause (if present) shall be one or more valid
          statements, separated by в—Ҡ for more than one statement.

   Examples:
      вҚқ short format. Valid in immediate execution and in defined functions
      вҚқ
      XвҶҗ5 в—Ҡ XвүҘ0 вҶ’вҶ’ X 'is positive' вҶҗвҶ’ X 'is negative' вҶҗвҶҗ
 5 is positive 


      вҚқ long format. Only possible in defined functions because immediate
      вҚқ execution works line by line (and parsing the first line would fail).

      вҚқ valid split into several lines (in a defined function)
      вҚқ
      вҲҮFOO X
       XвүҘ0             вҶ’вҶ’
       X 'is positive' вҶҗвҶ’
       X 'is negative' вҶҗвҶҗ
      вҲҮ
      FOO 5
 5 is positive 
      FOO ВҜ5
 ВҜ5 is negative 


      вҚқ invalid split into several lines: вҶҗвҶ’ spread over 2 lines.
      вҚқ FOO can be properly parsed, but calling FOO fails.
      вҚқ
      вҲҮFOO X
      XвүҘ0 вҶ’вҶ’ X 'is positive' вҶҗ
           вҶ’ X 'is negative' вҶҗвҶҗ
      вҲҮ
      FOO 5
SYNTAX ERROR
FOO[1]  X 'is positive'вҶҗ


      вҚқ invalid split into several lines: вҶҗвҶ’ is first token in line).
      вҚқ FOO is invalid and the вҲҮ-editor complains when closing FOO.
      вҚқ
      вҲҮFOO X
       XвүҘ0 вҶ’вҶ’ X 'is positive'
           вҶҗвҶ’ X 'is negative' вҶҗвҶҗ
      вҲҮ
NOTE: Invalid вҶҗвҶ’ at start of line 2
Error in function body in function line [2] of:
[0] FOO X
[1]        XвүҘ0 вҶ’вҶ’ X 'is positive'
[2]            вҶҗвҶ’ X 'is negative' вҶҗвҶҗ
Fatal error in defined function line [2]. You may now:
    change the faulty line  with:  [2] ..., or 
    delete the faulty line  with:  [вҲҶ2], or
    cancel editing with:  [вҶ’]вҲҮ.


   The recommended usage of corresponding вҶ’вҶ’, вҶҗвҶ’, and вҶҗвҶҗ token is to:

   вҖў either put them on the same line (short format), or else
   вҖў align all of them on the same column (long form), but
   вҖў never mix the short and long forms

   Like shown in the examples above.


