2.42 Matrix Product
===================

In standard APL, the inner product Z of two matrices A and B as known
from linear algebra, is:

      ZвҶҗA +.Г— B      вҚқ the most frequent special case of A f.g B

   However, the inner product in APL is more generic than the inner
product in linear algebra.  In the general case A f.g B may the
functions f and g also be non-scalar APL primitives or even defined
functions.  This generality is occasionally helpful, but comes with a
performance penalty since many argument checks are duplicated.  At the
same time A +.Г— B is by far the most frequent use of operator вҖҷ.вҖҷ.

   For this reason GNU APL also provides a more efficient dyadic
function вҲҳ (Matrix Product) for the special case +.Г— of the dyadic
operator вҖҷ.вҖҷ.  This function вҲҳ has been optimized for numeric arguments
and computes the matrix product as known from linear algebra.

   For two-dimensional matrices A and B function вҲҳ is the same as +.Г—:

   AвҲҳB вҶҗвҶ’ A +.Г— B

   Otherwise there are some subtle differences between вҲҳ and +.Г—:

   вҖў A +.Г— B allows A and B to be of any rank, while AвҲҳB raises a RANK
     ERROR if the rank of A or B is more than 2.
   вҖў With operator +.Г— the product of e.g.  a vector and a matrix (or
     vice versa) is a vector, usually understood as row-vector.  In
     contrast (and more similar to linear algebra) AвҲҳB is always a
     matrix, to preserve the distinction between row vectors and column
     vectors:

           MвҶҗ2 2вҚҙ1 2 3 4   вҚқ a matrix
           VвҶҗ10 11         вҚқ a vector
     
           M +.Г— V
     32 74
     
           MвҲҳV
     32
     74
     
           V +.Г— M
     43 64
     
           VвҲҳM
     43 64
     
           вҚҙM +.Г— V   вҚқ vector
     2
           вҚҙV +.Г— M   вҚқ vector
     2
           вҚҙVвҲҳM       вҚқ row vector
     1 2
           вҚҙMвҲҳV       вҚқ column vector
     2 1


